# Angular Naming Conventions

Follow these strict naming conventions for all Angular files:

## Components
- TypeScript: `*.component.ts`
- Template: `*.component.html`
- Styles: `*.component.scss` (or `.css`)
- Spec: `*.component.spec.ts`

Example:
```
login.component.ts
login.component.html
login.component.scss
login.component.spec.ts
```

## Modules
- Module: `*.module.ts`
- Routing Module: `*-routing.module.ts`

Example:
```
admin.module.ts
admin-routing.module.ts
```

## Services
- Service: `*.service.ts`
- Spec: `*.service.spec.ts`

Example:
```
auth.service.ts
auth.service.spec.ts
```

## Other Angular Files
- Directives: `*.directive.ts`
- Pipes: `*.pipe.ts`
- Guards: `*.guard.ts`
- Interceptors: `*.interceptor.ts`
- Resolvers: `*.resolver.ts`
- Validators: `*.validator.ts`
- Models/Interfaces: `*.model.ts` or `*.interface.ts`

## File Naming Rules
1. Use kebab-case for all file names (lowercase with hyphens)
2. Always include the file type suffix (component, service, module, etc.)
3. Keep names descriptive but concise
4. Group related files in the same directory

## Class Naming
- Components: PascalCase ending in `Component` (e.g., `LoginComponent`)
- Services: PascalCase ending in `Service` (e.g., `AuthService`)
- Modules: PascalCase ending in `Module` (e.g., `AdminModule`)
- Directives: PascalCase ending in `Directive`
- Pipes: PascalCase ending in `Pipe`
- Guards: PascalCase ending in `Guard`
